{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521402"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:33:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:33:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13605"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13605"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.44,0.05,0.02,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6218"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114513"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6218"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13605"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96514"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"125"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1167"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12484"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35821"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35831"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43426"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48055"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49434"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114513"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of worsening lower back pain. He describes the pain as constant, not relieved by rest, and worse at night. He reports unintentionally losing 8 kg over the past three months. He has a history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and polymyalgia rheumatica. His medications include metformin and prednisolone (which he has been taking for 12 months on a slow weaning regime for polymyalgia rheumatica). He denies any recent trauma or changes in bowel or bladder function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is mild tenderness over the lumbar spine. Range of movement of the lumbar spine is normal in all directions. No neurological deficits are noted.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prescribe non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs","Order a lumbar spine X-ray","Arrange urgent bone densitometry","Refer for physiotherapy","Order magnetic resonance imaging of the spine"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with multiple red flags for serious spinal pathology: significant unintentional weight loss and night pain. These features, combined with his long-term corticosteroid use, raise concern for underlying malignancy, infection, or pathological fracture requiring urgent investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the spine\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as it is the most sensitive and specific imaging modality for identifying spinal malignancy, infection, and other serious pathology. The patient\u0027s chronic corticosteroid use increases his risk of both infection and osteoporotic fractures. Early diagnosis is crucial for optimal outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-ray\u003C/strong\u003E of the lumbar spine, while useful for assessing structural abnormalities and fractures, has limited sensitivity for early malignancy or infection. It may delay appropriate diagnosis and management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs\u003C/strong\u003E may provide symptomatic relief but would be inappropriate as the initial management step given the concerning features suggesting serious underlying pathology. They also carry increased risk in a patient with diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhysiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E referral would be appropriate for mechanical back pain but is not the correct first step when red flags are present. Manipulation could potentially be harmful if there is underlying malignancy, infection, or pathological fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone densitometry\u003C/strong\u003E while relevant given the patient\u0027s long-term steroid use, is not the urgent priority given the red flag symptoms suggesting possible malignancy or other serious pathology. This investigation can be arranged after the acute presentation has been investigated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The presence of night pain and unexplained weight loss are red flags in patients presenting with back pain requiring urgent investigation.","MRI is the imaging modality of choice when serious pathology is suspected in back pain.","Long-term corticosteroid use is a risk factor for both osteoporosis and infection."],"references":["Jensen RK, Jensen TS, Koes B, Hartvigsen J. Prevalence of lumbar spinal stenosis in general and clinical populations: a systematic review and meta-analysis. Eur Spine J. 2020;29(9):2143-2163. doi:10.1007/s00586-020-06483-0","Diehn FE. Imaging of Spine Infection. Radiol Clin North Am. 2012 May;50(4):777-98. doi: 10.1016/j.rcl.2012.04.012.","Herzog RJ. The radiologic assessment for a lumbar disc herniation. Spine (Phila Pa 1976). 1996 Jan 1;21(1):19S-38S. doi: 10.1097/00007632-199601000-00005.","Knezevic NN, Candido KD, Vlaeyen JWS et al. Low back pain. Lancet 2021; 398:78-92."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96514"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13605"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96514"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-17T10:34:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T10:36:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6218"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114513"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationshi